{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17519683","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17519683"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:14:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:14:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13062"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13062","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13062"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.43,0.05,0.07,0.4,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5499"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"91342"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5499","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5499"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13062"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75091"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"136"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13152"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31237"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34937"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42843"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43902"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45351"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48276"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"91342","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/91342"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of persistent mid-back pain. She has a medical history of chronic alcohol use and was diagnosed with chronic pancreatitis two years ago. She does not take any regular medications. She continues to drink three to four glasses of wine daily. She does not smoke.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears thin with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination reveals mild epigastric tenderness. Skin changes are noted on her back which are non-palpable and non-tender (Image), with no involvement at any other location.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis for the skin changes?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Livedo reticularis","Tinea versicolor","Erythema migrans","Erythema ab igne","Pityriasis rosea"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe skin changes seen in this patient are characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003Eerythema ab igne\u003C/strong\u003E, a condition resulting from repeated exposure to heat. This reticulated pattern of hyperpigmentation and erythema typically develops over weeks to months due to prolonged contact with a heat source. In this case, the patient likely used hot water bottles or heating pads to alleviate the chronic back pain associated with her pancreatitis. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EErythema ab igne is a benign condition, but its presence should prompt investigation into the underlying cause of chronic pain, which in this case is already known to be chronic pancreatitis. Management should focus on treating the underlying pancreatitis and educating the patient about the risks of prolonged heat application.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELivedo reticularis\u003C/strong\u003E is a net-like, mottled, reddish-blue discoloration of the skin that can occur due to various underlying conditions, including autoimmune disorders or vascular problems. It typically affects the legs, although can also involve the trunk and arms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETinea versicolor\u003C/strong\u003E is a common fungal infection of the skin that causes small, discolored patches, usually on the chest and back. While it can affect the back, it does not present with a reticulated pattern and is not associated with heat application.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EErythema migrans\u003C/strong\u003E is the characteristic rash of Lyme disease, presenting as a bull\u0027s-eye pattern that expands over days. It is not associated with chronic heat application and would not persist for months.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPityriasis rosea\u003C/strong\u003E typically begins with a single, large pink patch (herald patch) followed by a widespread rash on the body. It does not present with a reticulated pattern and is not associated with heat exposure.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Erythema ab igne is a common sequela of chronic application of heat to relieve pain in conditions such as chronic pancreatitis."],"references":["Harview CL, Krinitsky A. Erythema Ab Igne: A Clinical Review. Cutis 2023;111:E33-E38.","The Australasian College of Dermatologists. Erythema Ab Igne [Internet]. ACD. Available from: https://www.dermcoll.edu.au/atoz/erythema-ab-igne/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75091"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13062"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20173"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20173","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20173"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/c11b22c6-8548-4f08-8606-556c568d8c96.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/c11b22c6-8548-4f08-8606-556c568d8c96.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":562,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75091","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75091"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-15T16:17:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-16T09:3